A national social insurance agency is redesigning the default architecture of a retirement savings program that determines the financial security of tens of millions of workers, and the policy design team needs a mission-critical decision tool that integrates behavioral economics evidence with the agency's legal, fiscal, and equity obligations. Build a high-stakes policy design app where the team articulates the choice architecture decisions on the table — default contribution rate, default investment allocation, auto-escalation schedule, opt-out mechanics, employer match structure — and for each decision documents the relevant behavioral evidence base. The app should let the team pull in the academic literature on present bias, hyperbolic discounting, intertemporal choice, prospect theory, loss aversion, the endowment effect, framing effects, nudge theory, and social preferences, attaching each study with its effect size, the population studied, the year, and the team's assessment of how transportable the finding is to the U.S. workforce population. The team then drafts the proposed default structure, with a behavioral rationale for each choice, and the app supports a structured red-teaming review where outside reviewers identify which behavioral assumptions are most load-bearing and whether the proposed defaults could harm subgroups whose reference-dependent preferences or social preferences differ from the modal worker (lower-income workers who may need the cash flow now and would be hurt by a high default). The app should produce the public comment package — the rule text, the regulatory impact analysis section on behavioral assumptions, the responses to anticipated objections from industry and consumer groups — and preserve every version because the rule will be litigated. It should also maintain a live registry of post-implementation surveillance: which subgroups opted out at higher rates than expected, where defaults may have nudged people into outcomes they would not have endorsed on reflection, and what the agency has learned for the next rulemaking cycle.